		"title"		: "The Night I Followed the Dog",
		"text"		: "1\n00:00:01,569 --> 00:00:06,439\nHi, Welcome to the Screen Actors Guild Foundation BookPALS.\n\n2\n00:00:06,439 --> 00:00:11,379\nI'm Amanda Bynes, you may know me from \"All That,\" or Nickelodeon's \"The Amanda Show,\" or  \"Big Fat Liar.\"\n\n3\n00:00:11,380 --> 00:00:16,020\nToday I'm going to be reading a story about a dog, and I have two dogs so I thought it was a pretty cool idea.\n\n4\n00:00:16,020 --> 00:00:20,560\nIt's called \"The Night I Followed the Dog.\" It's written and illustrated by Nina Laden.\n\n5\n00:00:22,250 --> 00:00:29,960\nI have a dog. Nothing exotic or special, just an ordinary dog. In fact I always thought he was a boring dog.\n\n6\n00:00:29,960 --> 00:00:37,000\nWhat I mean is he can fetch, roll over and shake hands, but mostly he sleeps and eats.\n\n7\n00:00:38,640 --> 00:00:42,300\nI used to think that our nextdoor neighbors had the best dog in the world.\n\n8\n00:00:42,300 --> 00:00:48,940\nTheir dog can sing and change the channels on the TV. Their dog always wins medals in obedience school.\n\n9\n00:00:48,940 --> 00:00:54,720\nBut I don't think their dog is so great now. Not since the night I followed my dog.\n\n10\n00:00:55,460 --> 00:00:59,900\nEvery night I let my dog out and he runs off into the darkness with his tail wagging.\n\n11\n00:00:59,900 --> 00:01:03,760\nThe next morning, I let him in and he heads straight for the food bowl.\n\n12\n00:01:03,760 --> 00:01:13,680\nBut one morning I knew something was funny, when I opened the door a little bit earlier than usual and I saw my dog jump out of a limousine wearing a tuxedo.\n\n13\n00:01:14,640 --> 00:01:20,520\nBefore I could look twice, he disappeared into the backyard and I opened the kitchen door and whistled.\n\n14\n00:01:20,520 --> 00:01:24,560\nWhen he came into the house he was the same as he always is. Hungry!\n\n15\n00:01:24,960 --> 00:01:27,960\nI really wasn't sure if I believed what I had seen.\n\n16\n00:01:27,960 --> 00:01:31,920\nSo that night I decided to follow him.\n\n17\n00:01:32,540 --> 00:01:39,100\nI wore dark clothing so I wouldn't be noticed, and I left my bicycle near the door so I'd have it close by.\n\n18\n00:01:39,110 --> 00:01:44,700\nWhen I let the dog out, I slipped out too. I took out the garbage so he wouldn't suspect anything.\n\n19\n00:01:44,700 --> 00:01:47,220\nThe dog went straight to his doghouse.\n\n20\n00:01:47,220 --> 00:01:53,660\nI saw a light go on inside. Slowly I snuck around the backyard and peeked into the doghouse.\n\n21\n00:01:54,380 --> 00:01:57,680\nThis is not the doghouse that I had helped build.\n\n22\n00:01:57,680 --> 00:02:03,000\nInside there was a living room, a bathroom, and a huge closet full of fancy clothes.\n\n23\n00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:08,140\nThe dog was in the bathroom. He was wearing a tuxedo and fumbling with a bowtie.\n\n24\n00:02:08,140 --> 00:02:13,600\nWhen he came out, he casually walked out of the doghouse, across the yard, and down the street.\n\n25\n00:02:14,160 --> 00:02:19,560\nI grabbed my bicycle and followed him. Two blocks later, I saw a limousine pull over.\n\n26\n00:02:19,560 --> 00:02:24,420\nThe dog got in and the car took off. I started peddling faster.\n\n27\n00:02:24,420 --> 00:02:30,560\nThe car headed across town. I thought I would lose them, but luckily they were stopped by a few red lights.\n\n28\n00:02:31,260 --> 00:02:35,839\nAfter a while, I found myself in a part of town that I'd never seen before.\n\n29\n00:02:35,840 --> 00:02:41,760\nThe buildings all seemed to be empty and it was very quiet. The limousine stopped.\n\n30\n00:02:42,300 --> 00:02:48,720\nI hid and watched my dog get out. He disappeared into a building and the limousine pulled away.\n\n31\n00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:55,540\nThere was nothing on the outside of the building, just two brass fire hydrants on either side of the entrance.\n\n32\n00:02:55,540 --> 00:03:02,380\nI opened the door. At the end of the hall there was a neon sign that said The Dog House. I crept closer.\n\n33\n00:03:02,380 --> 00:03:07,100\nIt looked like some kind of club. I decided to get a closer look.\n\n34\n00:03:08,109 --> 00:03:14,120\nThe moment I opened the door, two mean-looking bulldogs appeared and said, \"You can't come in here.\"\n\n35\n00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:21,700\nI didn't know what to say, so I said, \"But, but... I saw my dog. I mean, I think my dog's in here.\"\n\n36\n00:03:21,700 --> 00:03:26,460\nJust then, my dog walked over and said, \"It's okay boys, he's with me.\"\n\n37\n00:03:26,460 --> 00:03:30,600\nThe bulldog said, \"Sure boss, uh, whatever you say boss.\"\n\n38\n00:03:30,940 --> 00:03:34,920\nFor a minute, it seemed like forever, I waited.\n\n39\n00:03:34,920 --> 00:03:43,099\nThen my dog said, \"I knew you'd find out eventually. Well, now you know. This is my place.\"\n\n40\n00:03:43,099 --> 00:03:47,760\nI looked around. Finally I asked, \"What is this place?\"\n\n41\n00:03:47,760 --> 00:03:54,169\nMy dog said, \"This, this is a place where dogs come after a hard day.\n\n42\n00:03:54,169 --> 00:04:02,360\nIt's a place where we can relax. It's a place where we can talk about our problems with the mailman or with the poodle next door.\n\n43\n00:04:02,360 --> 00:04:10,760\nSee all the sofas? We can sit on the sofas here. We can get treats without having to lie down, roll over, or play dead.\n\n44\n00:04:10,760 --> 00:04:15,740\nAnd if we want to chew on a shoe or chase our tail, no one will stop us.\n\n45\n00:04:15,740 --> 00:04:25,780\nWe have no masters here, no leashes, and no rolled-up newspapers. This, this is a place where dogs can be dogs.\"\n\n46\n00:04:27,620 --> 00:04:34,080\nWe sat down. A cocker spaniel came by and asked me if I would like a bowl of water or some biscuits.\n\n47\n00:04:34,080 --> 00:04:37,639\nLittle by little dogs of all kinds started coming in.\n\n48\n00:04:37,640 --> 00:04:46,000\nSome danced. Some talked. They all looked at me a little funny, but when they saw who I was with, they smiled and shook my hand.\n\n49\n00:04:47,060 --> 00:04:53,600\nAt one point, my dog waved to an Afghan with a camera. She came over to our table and took a picture of us together.\n\n50\n00:04:53,700 --> 00:04:57,560\nBeing with my dog made me feel like a movie star.\n\n51\n00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:02,940\nJust when I was really starting to enjoy myself, I looked at my watch.\n\n52\n00:05:02,940 --> 00:05:07,460\nI told my dog I had to leave or I'd get in trouble. He nodded.\n\n53\n00:05:07,480 --> 00:05:13,840\nI think he was about to say something, but a glamorous greyhound grabbed his paw and whisked him onto the dance floor.\n\n54\n00:05:13,840 --> 00:05:17,719\nAs he was getting up, he tossed me the photo of the two of us.\n\n55\n00:05:17,720 --> 00:05:21,500\nThen he bowed slightly and disappeared into the crowd.\n\n56\n00:05:22,820 --> 00:05:25,340\nIt was way past my bedtime.\n\n57\n00:05:25,340 --> 00:05:35,280\nAs I peddled home into the cool night, I thought to myself, \"Now I'm really going to be in the doghouse. But then again, that might not be so bad.\"\n\n58\n00:05:35,780 --> 00:05:37,000\nThe End.\n\n59\n00:05:37,640 --> 00:05:42,820\nWhat'd you think? Yeah, I thought it was really great, too. I should go home and read this to my dogs.",
